Next, I'd like to give you an overview of the study. Please stop me if you have any questions. The COMET study is testing whether exercise affects memory, thinking and brain health in older adults. Many people, as they age, notice changes in how they think and remember. Research has found that physical activity is one of the most promising methods for improving brain health. We hope this study will help transform health-care recommendations in the future.

As a requirement for the study, you will be asked to exercise for 52-weeks (one full year). On average, it will be about 5 days per week of exercise for the full year. Most of your exercise would take place at a study-approved exercise facility, and the type of exercise you do for the year depends on the group you are randomized into. The randomization process is done by a computer and none of the tests you complete, or the study team can influence which group you get assigned to. We ask that anyone choosing to join the study is comfortable going to any of the 4 groups.

All groups are supervised by personal trainers who will monitor your progress and ensure you are exercising safely. Each week you will also be responsible for completing independent exercise sessions outside of working with your trainer. We start you out meeting with the personal trainer more frequently (3x/week) for the first 6-months (26-weeks) of the study and then we start to decrease the frequency you meet with your trainer, so you can become more independent with the exercise throughout the year. The 4 exercise groups are:

1. The Core & Fusion training group includes a flexibility, chair-yoga, balance, and stretching program each week for a total of 150 minutes

2. The Endurance exercise group does endurance/aerobics (like walking or cycling) at a moderate intensity for 150 minutes per week

3. The Weight Training group lifts weights (using mostly machines at the gym) two days per week in addition to yoga, balance and stretching (Core & Fusion) 3 days per week for a total of 150 minutes per week

4. The COMBO group, will do both 150 minutes of endurance training and two days (about 75 minutes) of weight training each week for a total of 225 minute per week

Aside from the year of exercise, you will also be required to complete several (~7) clinic visits throughout your participation. You would complete 3 separate visits at baseline, prior to starting the year of exercise. There would be 1 visit at 6-months of exercise. Then, 3 separate visits again after the full 52-weeks of exercise.

The first visit at baseline includes consent and a memory and thinking (cognitive) test. During consent we will talk about everything involved in the study. This is a good time to ask absolutely any questions. Consent takes about an hour and a half. During the memory and thinking test, you will be asked to do some assessments using paper and pencils or a computer. Our staff will help administer these and answer any questions you may have. The memory and thinking tests will last approximately 2.5 hours. We will give you breaks between tests if you get tired. You will repeat the memory and thinking testing halfway through the study (26-weeks) and again at the end of the study (52-weeks).

The study also involves physical fitness testing. At this visit, we will ask you to perform several sub-maximal and maximal fitness assessments including strength testing and a test that requires you to walk on a treadmill while breathing into a tube. This assessment is very similar to a treadmill stress test and will be done with trained specialists. We will also complete 2 blood draws and a DXA scan (full-body X-ray) to measure your muscle, bone, and fat (body composition). Total time for this visit is approximately 3-hours. You will repeat this visit again at the end of the study (at 52-weeks).

You would also complete MRI brain scans for the study. The MRI obtains images of your brain. No radiation is involved in these scans. This visit will likely take about 1.5 hours, but you will only be in the MRI machine for about 45 minutes. You will also repeat this visit at the end of the study (52-weeks).

The only other main component of the COMET study is completing surveys/questionnaires. All participants will be compensated for their participation, up to $520 for the completion of all aspects of the study. Between the baseline testing and exercise, your participation in the COMET study is expected to last about 15 months.

Section Header:
30-second Chair Rise - Number of full stands that can be completed in 30 seconds with arms folded across chest.

This should be completed on the wide, padded bench chair that typically sits against the west wall of the Exercise Physiology Lab.

Instruction: "With your arms crossed over your chest, move from a sitting position to a standing position and back as many times as you can until I say stop. Ready: Go."

Arm Curls - Sitting with unused hand in lap, the number of bicep curls with palm up that can be completed in 30 seconds holding a hand weight of 5 lbs (2.27 kg) for women; 8 lbs (3.63 kg) for men. Test begins with the hand and weight hanging down at the side of the body. The palm should rotate up during the curl-up phase then should return to handshake position at extension. Only count curls that go through the full range of motion.

This should be completed on the low, blue padded plinth seated next to the edge so that the arm and weight can dangle. Instruction: "Curl the weight up until your elbow is fully bent as many times as you can in 30 seconds. Ready: Go."

Chair Sit and Reach - From a sitting position at the edge of the chair, with dominant leg extended and both hands overlapped and reaching toward toes, the number of inches between middle fingers and tip of toe. Use dominant leg and allow a warm-up. Record to the nearest half inch. If the reach is short of the toes, record the distance as a minus "-" score. If the reach is past the toes record the distance as a normal number. Record to the nearest ½ inch.

This should be completed on the low, blue padded plinth that was just used for the Arm Curls. Instruction: "Extend the leg on the same side as the hand you write with and point your toes up to the ceiling. Keeping your leg extended and your knee as straight as possible, reach out as far as you can towards your toe. Ready: Go."

Section Header:
6-minute Walk distance in yards. (6MW)

Measure in yards, the distance that can be walked in the CTSU hall in 6 minutes. Set 2 cones, 27.3 yards (25 meters) apart. Start the timer when you say "Go" When the timer gets to 15s before the end of the test (5:45), tell the person that when you say "stop", they should stop where they are. Use the yellow wheel measurement tool in the CTSU to measure the number of feet walked to the nearest yard. You can multiply the number of lengths walked by 27.3 to get a whole number of lengths and add that to the wheel measure to get total number of yards, to the nearest whole yard. Instruction: "Walk as quickly as you feel safe and comfortable, around these cones for the next 6 minutes. Only the distance between the cones counts, so try to make sharp turns around the cones. You can stop if you need to, to rest, but if you stop try and get going again quickly because the timer keeps counting down. Talking can affect your performance so try not to talk unless something doesn't feel right. We will count your laps for you. Ready? Go."

Field Label: 1-RM data is expected to be missing

Chest Press Instructions

Show subject the machine. Demonstrate how the seat adjusts and how the load is selected. Select load and demonstrate slow, full ROM, reps. Position the subject on machine. Adjust seat so that the soles of the feet are flat on the ground and the knees are at approximately 90degrees. Choose warm-up load based on subjects gender, weight, build and history. This load should be light and forms the basis of your initial attempt. Have the subject demonstrate 2-second push and 2-second return through a full ROM.

Starting warm-up load guidance is as follows
Male = 0.66 * Body weight
Female = 0.48 * body weight

Recommendations based on warm-up load:
- If participant rated it as very light (RPE 9/20), double the warm-up load.
- If participant rated it as moderate (RPE (13/20), increase by 30%.
- If participant rated it as hard (RPE 17/20), increase to the next level (5-15 lbs).

Rest 3 min - Observation of this is critical to recharge ATP-PC.

See directions for increases above
Continue until participant is no longer successful- Final weight lifted is recorded as 1-RM.

Section Header:
VO2 Peak/Max Sufficiency.

The CTSU Exercise Physiologist will then set the participant up for the GXT by setting up the EKG and explaining the test.

For the COMET GXT, the pace will remain constant throughout the test. Starting grade will be set by the test leader, grade will be increased 2% every 2 minutes until the participant elects to terminate the test, the lead tester determines that maximal VO2 has been reached based on ACSM criteria, or the presence of relative or absolute indications for test termination according to ACSM guidelines occur. Participants may not hold on to the handrails during the test but may use fingers or light touch for balance.

Section Header:
Adverse Event or Event of Interest Overview

README: This form is designed in conjunction with automated emails to improve efficiency for study staff and investigators. Leave the Form Status as Incomplete or Unverified until an AE is ready for closeout. Marking the form status as Complete will send an email to the investigator for final signature. 

Fields were added to this instrument on 08/21/2023.

Field Label:
Is this an Event of Interest (EOI)?

Event of Interests are incidental findings or events that occur during baseline testing that do not rise to the level of urgent or emergent situations. Often these are diagnostic findings of existing problems, i.e. left-bundle branch block during GXT testing. It is often unclear if they are of new onset and are most likely pre-existing and asymptomatic.

Examples include asymptomatic ST segment depression on maximal exercise testing or a clear and obvious brain anomaly noted on MRI quality control.

If this is an Event of Interest, ensure this field is marked as Yes and continue to fill out the entirety of the AE form.
How did we learn of this AE/EOI?
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, Exercise Log | 2, Phone | 3, Trainer Informed | 4, In-Person Visit | 5, Other

Field Label:
AE Details / Narrative / Progress Note:

Please include a full, detailed narrative of the event. Provide as many details as possible so that any reviewer can fully grasp the situation. Be sure to track ongoing details until the event is completely resolved. For each new note, be sure to start a new line with the date of the note and end the note with initials. 

Guidance for questions to ask when gathering information

  • When did the event start?
  • How and where did the event occur?
  • If interventional study, when did the event begin in relation to the last dose of the intervention?
  • Is the event still on-going? If not, when did it cease?
  • Is the event persistent or does it come and go?
  • Was any treatment administered to alleviate the event? If so, what treatment (list meds, dose, when and how often taken)? Was the event alleviated by the treatment?
  • For pain-related AE's, may ask to rate pain on a scale of 1-10.
  • Did the event interfere with ability to complete daily activities? What type of activities? How was the participant limited? 
  • Did the participant seek care?
  • Did the participant go to the hospital? When? Where? Still there? Did they stay overnight? How long? What dates were they there? Be sure to consult study protocol for definition of hospitalization. 

Example for how to document AE and notes:

7/12/2023: Particpant rolled ankle on a stone while working in their garden at home in the afternoon on 7/11/23. Pt went to emergency care for imaging, which showed no structural damage. At doctor's suggestions, the pt has been icing, elevating, and using Advil. We were notified by phone on 7/12/2023. JC

7/29/2023: Pt feels symptoms have completely resolved. No longer feels pain in ankle and is able to walk without symptoms. Closing out AE. JC

Field Label:
Severity

Generic CTCAE 5.0 grades are listed below. Be sure to consult your protocol and the CTCAE 5.0.


Grade 1 Mild; asymptomatic or mild symptoms; clinical or diagnostic observations only; intervention not indicated.


Grade 2 Moderate; minimal, local or noninvasive intervention indicated; limiting age-appropriate instrumental ADL*.


Grade 3 Severe or medically significant but not immediately life-threatening; hospitalization or prolongation of hospitalization indicated; disabling; limiting self care ADL**.


Grade 4 Life-threatening consequences; urgent intervention indicated.


Grade 5 Death related to AE
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, Grade 1; Mild | 2, Grade 2; Moderate | 3, Grade 3; Severe | 4, Grade 4; Life Threatening | 5, Grade 5; Death related to AE

Field Label:
Relatedness

Suggested definitions using HSC and NIA guidance are provided below. Be sure to consult your protocol.

Definitely Related: The adverse event is clearly related to the investigational agent/procedure - i.e. an event that follows a reasonable temporal sequence from administration of the study intervention, follows a known or expected response pattern to the suspected intervention, that is confirmed by improvement on stopping and reappearance of the event on repeated exposure and that could not be reasonably explained by the known characteristics of the subject's clinical state.

Possibly Related: The adverse event is more likely than not attributable to study participation, i.e. an adverse event that follows a reasonable temporal sequence from administration of the study intervention follows a known or expected response pattern to the suspected intervention, but that could readily have been produced by a number of other factors.

Not Related: The adverse event is judged to be caused by the clinical state or clearly attributable to unrelated circumstances.

Expectedness

Standard HSC definitions of expectedness are below. Be sure to consult your study protocol and consent for expectedness. 

Expected: does NOT differ in nature, severity, or frequency from risk information previously reviewed by the IRB

Unexpected: differs in nature, severity, or frequency from risk information previously reviewed and approved by the IRB
This AE is related or probably related and unexpected; therefore, this AE should be reported to the KUMC IRB. Be sure to use the Reporting Section below.
If Unexpected: What is the rationale?
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, The event not described in available risk information currently | 2, The severity or frequency of the event was more than what was anticipated/described | 3, Other

Field Label:
Is this a Serious Adverse Event?

Guidelines for serious adverse events are below, but be sure to consult your study protocol.

Any adverse event that:
• Results in death
• Is life threatening, or places the participant at immediate risk of death from the event as it occurred
• Requires or prolongs hospitalization
• Causes persistent or significant disability or incapacity
• Results in congenital anomalies or birth defects
• Is another condition which investigators judge to represent significant hazards

Section Header:
Reporting Section

All internal adverse drug, device, and other events, serious or non-serious, that are unexpected and that are judged by the KUMC principal investigator to be related or probably related to participation in the research should be reported.

To review the updated KUMC guidance for reporting, see section 5.3 in this link to IRB SOP 05.0 Reviews of Ongoing Research.

Time Frames for reporting (see section 5.3.VI of IRB SOP 05.0 Reviews of Ongoing Research)

  1. Except for study deaths, internal problems must be reported to the IRB within five working days.
  2. For study deaths, see SOP Section 5.3.VI.C. Minimum reporting time is 24 hours, but reporting time depends on the situation.

Report Form (see section 5.3.VII of IRB SOP 05.0 Reviews of Ongoing Research)

  1. Investigators report the above listed problems using the eIRB system function of "Reportable New Information."
  2. A PDF of this adverse event may be submitted with the RNI as the required supplemental reporting form.

IRB Reporting Information

Reporting Form

Do not meet the IRB reporting criteria:

  • Study visits occurring outside the protocol required time frame due to participant schedule
  • Study activities performed close to, but not precisely at the time points specified in the protocol.

Meet the IRB reporting criteria:

  • Failure to obtain informed consent or re-consent when required by the IRB.
  • Modifying the protocol without IRB approval, except to avoid immediate hazard to subjects.
  • Conducting the research prior to IRB approval, during an IRB suspension or after IRB approval ends.

  • Noncompliance affects the rights and welfare of the subject(s).
  • Noncompliance affects the integrity of the research data.
  • Noncompliance increases the risk of harm for one or more subjects.
  • Noncompliance caused actual harm.
